Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:17 AM; Case called for Hearing. Defendant Brittney M McCoy in court.  Prosecuting attorney Chelsea Thompson in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Court notes the defendant is present without counsel today.  Defendant advises she filed a petition for court appointed attorney.  Court reviews the petition on the record and questions the defendant with respect to the petition.  Court will approve the petition for court appointed attorney and will order repayment at $75.00/month with the first payment due by 11/15/2022.  Court will adjourn in about 30 days for status of counsel.
Hearing scheduled for November 14, 2022 at 10:30 am.

Court inquires if the defendant plans to retain counsel in this matter.  Defendant advises she does want to be represented by an attorney and plans to retain counsel.  Court adjourns for status of counsel.  State notes the defendant can also be provided with the petition for court appointed attorney and also needs ID processing.  Court will provide the defendant with a petition for court appointed attorney and advises the defendant she must report to the Sheriff's Dept. for ID processing after court today.
